  "prompt": "Why is not possible to make serology exam in animal's blood with hemolysis?",
  "response": "When hemolysis occurs in a blood sample, it can interfere with serological tests for several important reasons:\n\n1. Hemoglobin interference\n- Free hemoglobin released from lysed red blood cells can:\n  - Absorb or block light in spectrophotometric measurements\n  - Cause color interference in test reactions\n  - Disrupt accurate antigen-antibody detection\n\n2. Altered sample composition\n- Red blood cell membrane breakdown affects:\n  - Sample protein concentration\n  - Potential cross-reactions\n  - Test reagent interactions\n\n3. Potential test result inaccuracies\n- Hemolysis can lead to:\n  - False positive results\n  - False negative results\n  - Unreliable quantitative measurements\n\n4. Biochemical interference\n- Hemolysis can:\n  - Alter sample pH\n  - Change enzyme activity\n  - Modify protein structure\n\n5. Technical limitations\n- Hemolyzed samples often cannot be processed due to:\n  - Compromised test integrity\n  - Potential misinterpretation risks\n\n6. Recommended practices\n- Always use non-hemolyzed blood samples\n- Carefully collect and handle blood specimens\n- Centrifuge and separate serum/plasma promptly\n\nThese factors make hemolyzed blood samples unsuitable for accurate serological testing.",
